         <entryFree xml:id="k000257" type="architectural feature">
            <term xml:id="term-k000257-1" xml:lang="zh-latn-pinyin-nt" source="#biblk000257-1">chonggong</term>
            <term xml:id="term-k000257-2" xml:lang="zh-Hant">重栱</term>
            <term xml:id="term-k000257-3" xml:lang="zh-Hans">重栱</term>
            <term xml:id="term-k000257-4" xml:lang="zh-latn-pinyin">chónggǒng</term>
            <term xml:id="term-k000257-5" xml:lang="zh-latn-wadegile">chung-kung</term>
            <term xml:id="term-k000257-6" xml:lang="zh-latn-wadegile" type="alternative" source="#biblk000257-2">ch'ung-kung</term>
            <idno type="URI">https://architecturasinica.org/keyword/k000257</idno>
            <note type="Note">
               <p xml:lang="en" source="#biblk000257-3">Literally “double bracket arms,” chongong refers to two bracket arms, one atop the other, placed parallel to the building plane to support squared beams (fang <term ref="/keyword/k000116">方</term>/枋). When used above projecting arms （tiaotou <term ref="/keyword/k000193">挑頭</term> or huagong <term ref="/keyword/k000172">華栱</term>) or the ang <term ref="/keyword/k000103">昂</term>, the lower arm is called a guazigong <term ref="/keyword/k000259">瓜子栱</term> and the upper arm is called a mangong <term ref="/keyword/k000155">慢栱</term>; when used as a fubigong <term ref="/keyword/k000029">扶壁栱</term>, the lower arm is called a nidaogong <term ref="/keyword/k000167">泥道栱</term> and the upper arm is called a mangong <term>慢栱</term> (Li 2009, 4.12b). The earliest use of chonggong we have found was by Li Linfu in the <term ref="/keyword/k000082">Tang</term> dynasty <title>Tang liudian 唐六典</title>  (ca. 739; Li et al. 1992, 592), a text which was used in reference to the ranking of palace architecture into the <term ref="/keyword/k000070">Qing</term> dynasty.</p>
               <p xml:lang="zh-Hant" source="#biblk000257-3">重栱指平行於屋身方向上下重疊的两层栱，其上承<term ref="/keyword/k000116">方</term>/枋：斗栱中<term ref="/keyword/k000193">挑頭</term>或<term ref="/keyword/k000103">昂</term>上的重栱，下為<term ref="/keyword/k000259">瓜子栱</term>，上為<term ref="/keyword/k000155">慢栱</term>；<term ref="/keyword/k000029">扶壁栱</term>中的重栱，下為<term ref="/keyword/k000167">泥道栱</term>，上為慢栱(李 2009, 4.12b)。在曆史文獻中最早見于<term ref="/keyword/k000082">唐</term>代《唐六典》(ca. 739; 李等 1992，592)，与宫室等级制度相关；并一直沿用至<term ref="/keyword/k000070">清</term>代。</p>
            </note>
